{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_c1053d9c60bb4995b86c6339","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# Technique: Tab-based Edit Views in Django\n2\t\n3\t## Motivation\n4\t\n5\t- A complex object (e.g. Product, Category, StaticBlock) has multiple different data areas (tabs: master data, prices, SEO, files, …).\n6\t- Each tab should be saved separately (POST processes only one form), so validation errors in one tab don't block the others.\n7\t- The UI shows all tabs in the same shell template with navigation. Tab content is included via `{% include %}`.\n8\t\n9\t---\n10\t\n11\t## Architecture\n12\t\n13\t### 1. Shell Template (Framework)\n14\t\n15\t- Contains tab navigation (`tabs`)\n16\t- Contains a `#tab-content` area\n17\t- Based on an `active_tab` variable that controls which partial is included.\n18\t\n19\t**Example: `templates/products/product_edit.html`**\n20\t\n21\t```django\n22\t<h1>Edit Product: {{ product.name }}</h1>\n23\t\n24\t<nav class=\"tabs\">\n25\t  {% for key, url in tabs %}\n26\t    <a href=\"{{ url }}\" class=\"{% if active_tab == key %}active{% endif %}\">\n27\t      {{ key|title }}\n28\t    </a>\n29\t  {% endfor %}\n30\t</nav>\n31\t\n32\t<div id=\"tab-content\">\n33\t  {% if active_tab == \"data\" %}\n34\t    {% include \"products/tabs/_data.html\" %}\n35\t  {% elif active_tab == \"seo\" %}\n36\t    {% include \"products/tabs/_seo.html\" %}\n37\t  {% elif active_tab == \"files\" %}\n38\t    {% include \"products/tabs/_files.html\" %}\n39\t  {% endif %}\n40\t</div>\n41\t```\n42\t\n43\t---\n44\t\n45\t### 2. Partials (Tab Contents)\n46\t\n47\tEach tab has a partial template that renders a form.  \n48\tThese receive their context directly from the view.\n49\t\n50\t**Example: `products/tabs/_data.html`**\n51\t\n52\t```django\n53\t<form method=\"post\">\n54\t  {% csrf_token %}\n55\t  {{ form.as_p }}\n56\t  <button type=\"submit\">Save Data</button>\n57\t</form>\n58\t```\n59\t\n60\t**Example: `products/tabs/_seo.html`**\n61\t\n62\t```django\n63\t<form method=\"post\">\n64\t  {% csrf_token %}\n65\t  {{ form.as_p }}\n66\t  <button type=\"submit\">Save SEO</button>\n67\t</form>\n68\t```\n69\t\n70\t---\n71\t\n72\t### 3. Shared Mixin\n73\t\n74\tA mixin builds the common context for all tabs: active tab, navigation, product object.\n75\t\n76\t**Example: `views_mixins.py`**\n77\t\n78\t```python\n79\tfrom django.urls import reverse\n80\tfrom django.shortcuts import get_object_or_404\n81\tfrom .models import Product\n82\t\n83\tclass ProductTabMixin:\n84\t    template_name = \"products/product_edit.html\"\n85\t    tab_name = None  # set in subclass: \"data\", \"seo\", ...\n86\t\n87\t    def get_product(self):\n88\t        return get_object_or_404(Product, pk=self.kwargs[\"pk\"])\n89\t\n90\t    def get_context_data(self, **kwargs):\n91\t        ctx = super().get_context_data(**kwargs)\n92\t        product = getattr(self, \"object\", None) or self.get_product()\n93\t        ctx[\"product\"] = product\n94\t        ctx[\"active_tab\"] = self.tab_name\n95\t        ctx[\"tabs\"] = [\n96\t            (\"data\", reverse(\"products:edit_data\", args=[product.pk])),\n97\t            (\"seo\",  reverse(\"products:edit_seo\", args=[product.pk])),\n98\t            (\"files\", reverse(\"products:edit_files\", args=[product.pk])),\n99\t        ]\n100\t        return ctx\n101\t```\n102\t\n103\t---\n104\t\n105\t### 4. Views per Tab\n106\t\n107\t#### Tab 1: Master Data (simple UpdateView)\n108\t\n109\t```python\n110\tfrom django.views.generic import UpdateView\n111\tfrom django.urls import reverse\n112\tfrom .forms import ProductForm\n113\t\n114\tclass ProductDataView(ProductTabMixin, UpdateView):\n115\t    model = Product\n116\t    form_class = ProductForm\n117\t    tab_name = \"data\"\n118\t\n119\t    def get_success_url(self):\n120\t        return reverse(\"products:edit_data\", args=[self.object.pk])\n121\t```\n122\t\n123\t#### Tab 2: SEO (OneToOne Relation, UpdateView with get_object)\n124\t\n125\t```python\n126\tfrom .models import SEO\n127\tfrom .forms import SEOForm\n128\t\n129\tclass ProductSEOView(ProductTabMixin, UpdateView):\n130\t    model = SEO\n131\t    form_class = SEOForm\n132\t    tab_name = \"seo\"\n133\t\n134\t    def get_object(self, queryset=None):\n135\t        product = self.get_product()\n136\t        seo, _ = SEO.objects.get_or_create(product=product)\n137\t        return seo\n138\t\n139\t    def get_success_url(self):\n140\t        return reverse(\"products:edit_seo\", args=[self.object.product.pk])\n141\t```\n142\t\n143\t#### Tab 3: Files (Upload + List, therefore FormView)\n144\t\n145\t```python\n146\tfrom django.views.generic import FormView\n147\tfrom django.db import transaction\n148\tfrom .models import StaticBlockFile\n149\tfrom .forms import FileForm\n150\t\n151\tclass ProductFilesView(ProductTabMixin, FormView):\n152\t    form_class = FileForm\n153\t    tab_name = \"files\"\n154\t\n155\t    def get_success_url(self):\n156\t        return reverse(\"products:edit_files\", args=[self.kwargs[\"pk\"]])\n157\t\n158\t    def form_valid(self, form):\n159\t        block = self.get_product()\n160\t        with transaction.atomic():\n161\t            file = form.save(commit=False)\n162\t            file.block = block\n163\t            file.save()\n164\t        return super().form_valid(form)\n165\t\n166\t    def get_context_data(self, **kwargs):\n167\t        ctx = super().get_context_data(**kwargs)\n168\t        ctx[\"files\"] = self.get_product().files.all()\n169\t        return ctx\n170\t```\n171\t\n172\t---\n173\t\n174\t### 5. URLs\n175\t\n176\t**Example: `urls.py`**\n177\t\n178\t```python\n179\tfrom django.urls import path\n180\tfrom .views import ProductDataView, ProductSEOView, ProductFilesView\n181\t\n182\tapp_name = \"products\"\n183\t\n184\turlpatterns = [\n185\t    path(\"<int:pk>/edit/data/\", ProductDataView.as_view(), name=\"edit_data\"),\n186\t    path(\"<int:pk>/edit/seo/\", ProductSEOView.as_view(), name=\"edit_seo\"),\n187\t    path(\"<int:pk>/edit/files/\", ProductFilesView.as_view(), name=\"edit_files\"),\n188\t]\n189\t```\n190\t\n191\t---\n192\t\n193\t## User Flow\n194\t\n195\t1. Click on \"Data\" → `/edit/data/`  \n196\t   → renders Shell + _data.html\n197\t2. Click on \"SEO\" → `/edit/seo/`  \n198\t   → renders Shell + _seo.html\n199\t3. Click on \"Files\" → `/edit/files/`  \n200\t   → renders Shell + _files.html\n201\t\n202\t- Always the same shell, only `active_tab` changes.\n203\t- POST processes only the form of the active tab.\n204\t\n205\t---\n206\t\n207\t## Advantages of this Technique\n208\t\n209\t- Only **one central view** for the entire object\n210\t- Good extensibility for additional tabs\n211\t- Tab switching triggers a full request (no JS necessary)\n212\t- Flexible markup via `{% include %}`\n213\t\n214\t---\n215\t\n216\t## Optional\n217\t\n218\t- Define tabs as URLs too: `/edit/?tab=data`, `/edit/?tab=files`\n219\t- Form validation per tab\n220\t- Integration of formsets or additional context data per tab\n221\t\n222\t---\n223\t\n224\t## Modal System\n225\t\n226\t### Overview\n227\t\n228\tThe management interface uses a size-specific modal system to provide optimal user experience. Instead of resizing modals dynamically (which causes visual flicker), we use dedicated modal snippets for different content types.\n229\t\n230\t### Modal Snippets\n231\t\n232\t**Structure: `templates/manage/snippets/modals/`**\n233\t\n234\t```\n235\tmodals/\n236\t├── modal-sm.html     # Small modals (confirmations, alerts)\n237\t├── modal-lg.html     # Large modals (forms, data entry)\n238\t└── modal-xl.html     # Extra large modals (previews, complex content)\n239\t```\n240\t\n241\t**Example: `modal-lg.html`**\n242\t\n243\t```django\n244\t{% load i18n %}\n245\t<div class=\"modal\" id=\"lfs-modal-lg\" tabindex=\"-1\" aria-hidden=\"true\">\n246\t    <div class=\"modal-dialog modal-lg\">\n247\t        <div class=\"modal-content\">\n248\t            <div class=\"modal-header\">\n249\t                <h5 class=\"modal-title\" id=\"modal-title-lg\"></h5>\n250\t                <button type=\"button\" class=\"btn-close\" data-bs-dismiss=\"modal\" aria-label=\"{% trans 'Close' %}\"></button>\n251\t            </div>\n252\t            <div class=\"modal-body\" id=\"modal-body-lg\"></div>\n253\t        </div>\n254\t    </div>\n255\t</div>\n256\t```\n257\t\n258\t### JavaScript Integration\n259\t\n260\t**File: `static/lfs/js/management/shared.js`**\n261\t\n262\t```javascript\n263\tdocument.addEventListener('htmx:afterSwap', evt => {\n264\t    const targetId = evt.detail.target?.id;\n265\t    let modalEl;\n266\t    \n267\t    // Target-based modal selection\n268\t    if (targetId === \"modal-body-sm\") {\n269\t        modalEl = document.getElementById('lfs-modal-sm');\n270\t    } else if (targetId === \"modal-body-lg\") {\n271\t        modalEl = document.getElementById('lfs-modal-lg');\n272\t    } else if (targetId === \"modal-body-xl\") {\n273\t        modalEl = document.getElementById('lfs-modal-xl');\n274\t    }\n275\t    \n276\t    if (modalEl) {\n277\t        let modalInstance = bootstrap.Modal.getInstance(modalEl);\n278\t        if (!modalInstance) {\n279\t            modalInstance = new bootstrap.Modal(modalEl);\n280\t        }\n281\t        if (!modalEl.classList.contains('show')) {\n282\t            modalInstance.show();\n283\t        }\n284\t    }\n285\t});\n286\t```\n287\t\n288\t### Usage in Templates\n289\t\n290\t**Button targeting specific modal size:**\n291\t\n292\t```django\n293\t<!-- For forms/data entry -->\n294\t<button hx-get=\"{% url 'add_static_block' %}\" \n295\t        hx-target=\"#modal-body-lg\"\n296\t        hx-swap=\"innerHTML\">\n297\t    Add Static Block\n298\t</button>\n299\t\n300\t<!-- For previews/large content -->\n301\t<button hx-get=\"{% url 'preview_static_block' pk %}\" \n302\t        hx-target=\"#modal-body-xl\"\n303\t        hx-swap=\"innerHTML\">\n304\t    Preview\n305\t</button>\n306\t```\n307\t\n308\t**Including modals in templates:**\n309\t\n310\t```django\n311\t{% extends \"manage/base.html\" %}\n312\t\n313\t{% block content %}\n314\t    <!-- Your page content -->\n315\t    \n316\t    <!-- Include required modal sizes -->\n317\t    {% include 'manage/snippets/modals/modal-lg.html' %}\n318\t    {% include 'manage/snippets/modals/modal-xl.html' %}\n319\t{% endblock %}\n320\t```\n321\t\n322\t**Modal content templates:**\n323\t\n324\t```django\n325\t<!-- add_static_block.html -->\n326\t{% load i18n crispy_forms_tags %}\n327\t\n328\t<h5 id=\"modal-title-lg\" class=\"modal-title\" hx-swap-oob=\"true\">\n329\t    {% trans 'Add Static Block' %}\n330\t</h5>\n331\t<form method=\"post\" hx-post=\"{% url 'add_static_block' %}\" hx-target=\"#modal-body-lg\">\n332\t    {% csrf_token %}\n333\t    {{ form|crispy }}\n334\t    <div class=\"mt-3\">\n335\t        <button type=\"submit\" class=\"btn btn-primary\">{% trans 'Save' %}</button>\n336\t        <button type=\"button\" class=\"btn btn-secondary\" data-bs-dismiss=\"modal\">\n337\t            {% trans 'Cancel' %}\n338\t        </button>\n339\t    </div>\n340\t</form>\n341\t```\n342\t\n343\t### Advantages\n344\t\n345\t**1. No Visual Flicker**\n346\t- Fixed modal sizes prevent resize animations\n347\t- Better user experience with instant, stable modals\n348\t\n349\t**2. Semantic Sizing**\n350\t- Each modal size has a clear purpose:\n351\t  - `modal-sm`: Quick confirmations, alerts\n352\t  - `modal-lg`: Standard forms, data entry\n353\t  - `modal-xl`: Content-heavy previews, complex displays\n354\t\n355\t**3. Performance**\n356\t- No JavaScript modal resizing overhead\n357\t- Modals initialize with final dimensions immediately\n358\t\n359\t**4. Maintainability**\n360\t- Reusable modal snippets across templates\n361\t- Centralized modal logic in `shared.js`\n362\t- Clear separation of concerns\n363\t\n364\t**5. Extensibility**\n365\t- Easy to add new modal sizes\n366\t- Simple button-to-modal mapping via `hx-target`\n367\t- Consistent pattern across the application\n368\t\n369\t### Implementation Notes\n370\t\n371\t- Each modal has unique IDs (`lfs-modal-sm`, `lfs-modal-lg`, `lfs-modal-xl`)\n372\t- Modal titles use size-specific IDs (`modal-title-sm`, `modal-title-lg`, `modal-title-xl`)\n373\t- HTMX `hx-swap-oob=\"true\"` updates modal titles dynamically\n374\t- JavaScript automatically detects target and shows appropriate modal\n375\t\n376\tThis approach scales well and provides a consistent, flicker-free modal experience throughout the management interface.\n377\t\n378\t## Note\n379\t\n380\tWhen tabs **become more complex** (e.g. many dependent fields, dynamic file uploads etc.), you can later switch to `htmx` or real `FormView` subcomponents.  \n381\tThe structure shown here works well as a scalable foundation for future expansion.\n382\t\n383\t# Frontend Dependencies and Vendor Assets\n384\t\n385\tFrontend libraries are managed through `package.json`. Running `npm run setup` first executes `npm install` to install all dependencies into `node_modules`, and then runs `npm run vendor:update`. The vendor update step starts by cleaning `static/lfs/manage/vendor/*` and then copies the required third-party assets (JavaScript, CSS, and fonts) from `node_modules` into `static/lfs/manage/vendor/...`."}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"f40d81cd-a8e1-4d99-9824-3e751d9ffb35","uuid":"242a54b2-c616-4ea8-85fc-79bbb154f110","timestamp":"2026-04-08T21:52:56.096Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/workspace/lfs/manage/README.md","content":"# Technique: Tab-based Edit Views in Django\n\n## Motivation\n\n- A complex object (e.g. Product, Category, StaticBlock) has multiple different data areas (tabs: master data, prices, SEO, files, …).\n- Each tab should be saved separately (POST processes only one form), so validation errors in one tab don't block the others.\n- The UI shows all tabs in the same shell template with navigation. Tab content is included via `{% include %}`.\n\n---\n\n## Architecture\n\n### 1. Shell Template (Framework)\n\n- Contains tab navigation (`tabs`)\n- Contains a `#tab-content` area\n- Based on an `active_tab` variable that controls which partial is included.\n\n**Example: `templates/products/product_edit.html`**\n\n```django\n<h1>Edit Product: {{ product.name }}</h1>\n\n<nav class=\"tabs\">\n  {% for key, url in tabs %}\n    <a href=\"{{ url }}\" class=\"{% if active_tab == key %}active{% endif %}\">\n      {{ key|title }}\n    </a>\n  {% endfor %}\n</nav>\n\n<div id=\"tab-content\">\n  {% if active_tab == \"data\" %}\n    {% include \"products/tabs/_data.html\" %}\n  {% elif active_tab == \"seo\" %}\n    {% include \"products/tabs/_seo.html\" %}\n  {% elif active_tab == \"files\" %}\n    {% include \"products/tabs/_files.html\" %}\n  {% endif %}\n</div>\n```\n\n---\n\n### 2. Partials (Tab Contents)\n\nEach tab has a partial template that renders a form.  \nThese receive their context directly from the view.\n\n**Example: `products/tabs/_data.html`**\n\n```django\n<form method=\"post\">\n  {% csrf_token %}\n  {{ form.as_p }}\n  <button type=\"submit\">Save Data</button>\n</form>\n```\n\n**Example: `products/tabs/_seo.html`**\n\n```django\n<form method=\"post\">\n  {% csrf_token %}\n  {{ form.as_p }}\n  <button type=\"submit\">Save SEO</button>\n</form>\n```\n\n---\n\n### 3. Shared Mixin\n\nA mixin builds the common context for all tabs: active tab, navigation, product object.\n\n**Example: `views_mixins.py`**\n\n```python\nfrom django.urls import reverse\nfrom django.shortcuts import get_object_or_404\nfrom .models import Product\n\nclass ProductTabMixin:\n    template_name = \"products/product_edit.html\"\n    tab_name = None  # set in subclass: \"data\", \"seo\", ...\n\n    def get_product(self):\n        return get_object_or_404(Product, pk=self.kwargs[\"pk\"])\n\n    def get_context_data(self, **kwargs):\n        ctx = super().get_context_data(**kwargs)\n        product = getattr(self, \"object\", None) or self.get_product()\n        ctx[\"product\"] = product\n        ctx[\"active_tab\"] = self.tab_name\n        ctx[\"tabs\"] = [\n            (\"data\", reverse(\"products:edit_data\", args=[product.pk])),\n            (\"seo\",  reverse(\"products:edit_seo\", args=[product.pk])),\n            (\"files\", reverse(\"products:edit_files\", args=[product.pk])),\n        ]\n        return ctx\n```\n\n---\n\n### 4. Views per Tab\n\n#### Tab 1: Master Data (simple UpdateView)\n\n```python\nfrom django.views.generic import UpdateView\nfrom django.urls import reverse\nfrom .forms import ProductForm\n\nclass ProductDataView(ProductTabMixin, UpdateView):\n    model = Product\n    form_class = ProductForm\n    tab_name = \"data\"\n\n    def get_success_url(self):\n        return reverse(\"products:edit_data\", args=[self.object.pk])\n```\n\n#### Tab 2: SEO (OneToOne Relation, UpdateView with get_object)\n\n```python\nfrom .models import SEO\nfrom .forms import SEOForm\n\nclass ProductSEOView(ProductTabMixin, UpdateView):\n    model = SEO\n    form_class = SEOForm\n    tab_name = \"seo\"\n\n    def get_object(self, queryset=None):\n        product = self.get_product()\n        seo, _ = SEO.objects.get_or_create(product=product)\n        return seo\n\n    def get_success_url(self):\n        return reverse(\"products:edit_seo\", args=[self.object.product.pk])\n```\n\n#### Tab 3: Files (Upload + List, therefore FormView)\n\n```python\nfrom django.views.generic import FormView\nfrom django.db import transaction\nfrom .models import StaticBlockFile\nfrom .forms import FileForm\n\nclass ProductFilesView(ProductTabMixin, FormView):\n    form_class = FileForm\n    tab_name = \"files\"\n\n    def get_success_url(self):\n        return reverse(\"products:edit_files\", args=[self.kwargs[\"pk\"]])\n\n    def form_valid(self, form):\n        block = self.get_product()\n        with transaction.atomic():\n            file = form.save(commit=False)\n            file.block = block\n            file.save()\n        return super().form_valid(form)\n\n    def get_context_data(self, **kwargs):\n        ctx = super().get_context_data(**kwargs)\n        ctx[\"files\"] = self.get_product().files.all()\n        return ctx\n```\n\n---\n\n### 5. URLs\n\n**Example: `urls.py`**\n\n```python\nfrom django.urls import path\nfrom .views import ProductDataView, ProductSEOView, ProductFilesView\n\napp_name = \"products\"\n\nurlpatterns = [\n    path(\"<int:pk>/edit/data/\", ProductDataView.as_view(), name=\"edit_data\"),\n    path(\"<int:pk>/edit/seo/\", ProductSEOView.as_view(), name=\"edit_seo\"),\n    path(\"<int:pk>/edit/files/\", ProductFilesView.as_view(), name=\"edit_files\"),\n]\n```\n\n---\n\n## User Flow\n\n1. Click on \"Data\" → `/edit/data/`  \n   → renders Shell + _data.html\n2. Click on \"SEO\" → `/edit/seo/`  \n   → renders Shell + _seo.html\n3. Click on \"Files\" → `/edit/files/`  \n   → renders Shell + _files.html\n\n- Always the same shell, only `active_tab` changes.\n- POST processes only the form of the active tab.\n\n---\n\n## Advantages of this Technique\n\n- Only **one central view** for the entire object\n- Good extensibility for additional tabs\n- Tab switching triggers a full request (no JS necessary)\n- Flexible markup via `{% include %}`\n\n---\n\n## Optional\n\n- Define tabs as URLs too: `/edit/?tab=data`, `/edit/?tab=files`\n- Form validation per tab\n- Integration of formsets or additional context data per tab\n\n---\n\n## Modal System\n\n### Overview\n\nThe management interface uses a size-specific modal system to provide optimal user experience. Instead of resizing modals dynamically (which causes visual flicker), we use dedicated modal snippets for different content types.\n\n### Modal Snippets\n\n**Structure: `templates/manage/snippets/modals/`**\n\n```\nmodals/\n├── modal-sm.html     # Small modals (confirmations, alerts)\n├── modal-lg.html     # Large modals (forms, data entry)\n└── modal-xl.html     # Extra large modals (previews, complex content)\n```\n\n**Example: `modal-lg.html`**\n\n```django\n{% load i18n %}\n<div class=\"modal\" id=\"lfs-modal-lg\" tabindex=\"-1\" aria-hidden=\"true\">\n    <div class=\"modal-dialog modal-lg\">\n        <div class=\"modal-content\">\n            <div class=\"modal-header\">\n                <h5 class=\"modal-title\" id=\"modal-title-lg\"></h5>\n                <button type=\"button\" class=\"btn-close\" data-bs-dismiss=\"modal\" aria-label=\"{% trans 'Close' %}\"></button>\n            </div>\n            <div class=\"modal-body\" id=\"modal-body-lg\"></div>\n        </div>\n    </div>\n</div>\n```\n\n### JavaScript Integration\n\n**File: `static/lfs/js/management/shared.js`**\n\n```javascript\ndocument.addEventListener('htmx:afterSwap', evt => {\n    const targetId = evt.detail.target?.id;\n    let modalEl;\n    \n    // Target-based modal selection\n    if (targetId === \"modal-body-sm\") {\n        modalEl = document.getElementById('lfs-modal-sm');\n    } else if (targetId === \"modal-body-lg\") {\n        modalEl = document.getElementById('lfs-modal-lg');\n    } else if (targetId === \"modal-body-xl\") {\n        modalEl = document.getElementById('lfs-modal-xl');\n    }\n    \n    if (modalEl) {\n        let modalInstance = bootstrap.Modal.getInstance(modalEl);\n        if (!modalInstance) {\n            modalInstance = new bootstrap.Modal(modalEl);\n        }\n        if (!modalEl.classList.contains('show')) {\n            modalInstance.show();\n        }\n    }\n});\n```\n\n### Usage in Templates\n\n**Button targeting specific modal size:**\n\n```django\n<!-- For forms/data entry -->\n<button hx-get=\"{% url 'add_static_block' %}\" \n        hx-target=\"#modal-body-lg\"\n        hx-swap=\"innerHTML\">\n    Add Static Block\n</button>\n\n<!-- For previews/large content -->\n<button hx-get=\"{% url 'preview_static_block' pk %}\" \n        hx-target=\"#modal-body-xl\"\n        hx-swap=\"innerHTML\">\n    Preview\n</button>\n```\n\n**Including modals in templates:**\n\n```django\n{% extends \"manage/base.html\" %}\n\n{% block content %}\n    <!-- Your page content -->\n    \n    <!-- Include required modal sizes -->\n    {% include 'manage/snippets/modals/modal-lg.html' %}\n    {% include 'manage/snippets/modals/modal-xl.html' %}\n{% endblock %}\n```\n\n**Modal content templates:**\n\n```django\n<!-- add_static_block.html -->\n{% load i18n crispy_forms_tags %}\n\n<h5 id=\"modal-title-lg\" class=\"modal-title\" hx-swap-oob=\"true\">\n    {% trans 'Add Static Block' %}\n</h5>\n<form method=\"post\" hx-post=\"{% url 'add_static_block' %}\" hx-target=\"#modal-body-lg\">\n    {% csrf_token %}\n    {{ form|crispy }}\n    <div class=\"mt-3\">\n        <button type=\"submit\" class=\"btn btn-primary\">{% trans 'Save' %}</button>\n        <button type=\"button\" class=\"btn btn-secondary\" data-bs-dismiss=\"modal\">\n            {% trans 'Cancel' %}\n        </button>\n    </div>\n</form>\n```\n\n### Advantages\n\n**1. No Visual Flicker**\n- Fixed modal sizes prevent resize animations\n- Better user experience with instant, stable modals\n\n**2. Semantic Sizing**\n- Each modal size has a clear purpose:\n  - `modal-sm`: Quick confirmations, alerts\n  - `modal-lg`: Standard forms, data entry\n  - `modal-xl`: Content-heavy previews, complex displays\n\n**3. Performance**\n- No JavaScript modal resizing overhead\n- Modals initialize with final dimensions immediately\n\n**4. Maintainability**\n- Reusable modal snippets across templates\n- Centralized modal logic in `shared.js`\n- Clear separation of concerns\n\n**5. Extensibility**\n- Easy to add new modal sizes\n- Simple button-to-modal mapping via `hx-target`\n- Consistent pattern across the application\n\n### Implementation Notes\n\n- Each modal has unique IDs (`lfs-modal-sm`, `lfs-modal-lg`, `lfs-modal-xl`)\n- Modal titles use size-specific IDs (`modal-title-sm`, `modal-title-lg`, `modal-title-xl`)\n- HTMX `hx-swap-oob=\"true\"` updates modal titles dynamically\n- JavaScript automatically detects target and shows appropriate modal\n\nThis approach scales well and provides a consistent, flicker-free modal experience throughout the management interface.\n\n## Note\n\nWhen tabs **become more complex** (e.g. many dependent fields, dynamic file uploads etc.), you can later switch to `htmx` or real `FormView` subcomponents.  \nThe structure shown here works well as a scalable foundation for future expansion.\n\n# Frontend Dependencies and Vendor Assets\n\nFrontend libraries are managed through `package.json`. Running `npm run setup` first executes `npm install` to install all dependencies into `node_modules`, and then runs `npm run vendor:update`. The vendor update step starts by cleaning `static/lfs/manage/vendor/*` and then copies the required third-party assets (JavaScript, CSS, and fonts) from `node_modules` into `static/lfs/manage/vendor/...`.","numLines":385,"startLine":1,"totalLines":385}}}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_b644479c5bff4646b089a2e6","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# Product Management Forms\n2\t\n3\t## Manual Form Rendering Decision\n4\t\n5\tProduct management forms are rendered manually field by field to display parent product values alongside variant input fields. This approach enables clear visualization of inherited vs. overridden values in product variants.\n6\t\n7\t### Rationale\n8\t- Crispy Forms helper proved insufficiently flexible for this specific UI requirement\n9\t- Manual rendering provides better control over the variant/parent value display layout\n10\t- Future evaluation of alternative form rendering libraries may be considered\n11\t\n12\t### Implementation Details\n13\t- Forms use Bootstrap grid system (col-md-8 for inputs, col-md-4 for parent values)\n14\t- Parent values are displayed using `form-control-plaintext` class\n15\t- Variant-specific checkboxes control field inheritance behavior\n16\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"f40d81cd-a8e1-4d99-9824-3e751d9ffb35","uuid":"20d07ef5-00d7-4e9f-8c50-36b8e17d2982","timestamp":"2026-04-08T21:52:56.098Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/workspace/lfs/manage/DECISIONS.md","content":"# Product Management Forms\n\n## Manual Form Rendering Decision\n\nProduct management forms are rendered manually field by field to display parent product values alongside variant input fields. This approach enables clear visualization of inherited vs. overridden values in product variants.\n\n### Rationale\n- Crispy Forms helper proved insufficiently flexible for this specific UI requirement\n- Manual rendering provides better control over the variant/parent value display layout\n- Future evaluation of alternative form rendering libraries may be considered\n\n### Implementation Details\n- Forms use Bootstrap grid system (col-md-8 for inputs, col-md-4 for parent values)\n- Parent values are displayed using `form-control-plaintext` class\n- Variant-specific checkboxes control field inheritance behavior\n","numLines":16,"startLine":1,"totalLines":16}}}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_d43255cc972f4146b630c4ad","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t.. index:: Testing LFS\n2\t\n3\t===========\n4\tTesting LFS\n5\t===========\n6\t\n7\tThis section describes how to test LFS.\n8\t\n9\tOverview\n10\t========\n11\t\n12\tTesting is based on `nose <http://readthedocs.org/docs/nose/en/latest/>`_ and\n13\t`django-nose <http://pypi.python.org/pypi/django-nose>`_.\n14\t\n15\tExamples\n16\t========\n17\t\n18\tTest everything::\n19\t\n20\t    $ bin/django test lfs.core\n21\t\n22\tTest everything with coverage (you'll find the coverage report in the current\n23\tdirectory)::\n24\t\n25\t    $ bin/django test lfs.core --with-coverage --cover-package=lfs --cover-html\n26\t\n27\tTest only the catalog::\n28\t\n29\t    $ bin/django test lfs.catalog\n30\t\n31\tTest only the catalog with coverage (you'll find the coverage report in the\n32\tcurrent directory)::\n33\t\n34\t    $ bin/django test lfs.catalog --with-coverage --cover-package=lfs.catalog --cover-html\n35\t\n36\tTest only one method without capturing the output (this is helpful if you want\n37\tto debug a test with pdb)::\n38\t\n39\t    $ bin/django test lfs.catalog.tests:ViewsTestCase.test_file -s\n40\t\n41\tSee also\n42\t========\n43\t\n44\t* `nose <http://readthedocs.org/docs/nose/en/latest/>`_\n45\t* `nose options <http://readthedocs.org/docs/nose/en/latest/usage.html#options>`_\n46\t* `django-nose <http://pypi.python.org/pypi/django-nose>`_\n47\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"f40d81cd-a8e1-4d99-9824-3e751d9ffb35","uuid":"e8501167-f257-4c7c-979b-7e7fc0cf7884","timestamp":"2026-04-08T21:52:56.099Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/workspace/docs/developer/testing.rst","content":".. index:: Testing LFS\n\n===========\nTesting LFS\n===========\n\nThis section describes how to test LFS.\n\nOverview\n========\n\nTesting is based on `nose <http://readthedocs.org/docs/nose/en/latest/>`_ and\n`django-nose <http://pypi.python.org/pypi/django-nose>`_.\n\nExamples\n========\n\nTest everything::\n\n    $ bin/django test lfs.core\n\nTest everything with coverage (you'll find the coverage report in the current\ndirectory)::\n\n    $ bin/django test lfs.core --with-coverage --cover-package=lfs --cover-html\n\nTest only the catalog::\n\n    $ bin/django test lfs.catalog\n\nTest only the catalog with coverage (you'll find the coverage report in the\ncurrent directory)::\n\n    $ bin/django test lfs.catalog --with-coverage --cover-package=lfs.catalog --cover-html\n\nTest only one method without capturing the output (this is helpful if you want\nto debug a test with pdb)::\n\n    $ bin/django test lfs.catalog.tests:ViewsTestCase.test_file -s\n\nSee also\n========\n\n* `nose <http://readthedocs.org/docs/nose/en/latest/>`_\n* `nose options <http://readthedocs.org/docs/nose/en/latest/usage.html#options>`_\n* `django-nose <http://pypi.python.org/pypi/django-nose>`_\n","numLines":47,"startLine":1,"totalLines":47}}}
